{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393347387/1938032401/0363.xml":{"full_text":"pMcntf\nPublished Every Evening Except Sundays\nand Holidays by\nTHE WATERBURY DEMOCRAT, INO.\nDemocrat Building, Water bury, Conn.\nSubscription Rates. Payable in Advance\nOne Year.$9.00 One Month. 75c\nSix Months.$4.50 One Week. 18c\nMember of Audit Bureau of Circulation\nThe Democrat will not return manuscript sent\nin for publication unless accompanied by postage.\nNo attention paid anonymous communications.\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 24, 1938\nA Thought for Today\nAnd Asa did that which was good and right\nin the eyes of the Lord his God.\u2014II Chronicles\n14:2.\nNo man has a right to do as he pleases, except\nwhen he pleases to do right.\u2014C. Simmons.\nEstablished 1881\nDial 4-2121\nAll Departments\nDial 4-2121\nAll Departments\nA Leader in the Right Direction\nIt becomes more and more noticeable\nthat Eamon De Valera, prime minister\nof Eire, is regarded as one of the world\u2019s\noutstanding leaders. Today when dic\ntators are in the limelight there are com\nmentators that include him in the \u201cdic\ntator\u201d class. There is, however, a vast\ndifference between the dictatorship of\nthe prime minister of Eire and that of\nother conspicuous ones of these times.\nIn his leadership \u201cDev,\u201d as he is famil\niarly known in Ireland, has not created,\nnor does he seek to create a totalitarian\nstate, though he has brought about some\nradical changes since he first became\npresident of the executive council of the\nformer Irish Free State.\nIndustrially Ireland has expanded of\nlate years. Her natural resources are\nmany. The natural beauties of the coun\ntry offer much in personal enjoyment, and\nthe fertile land possesses much that can\nbe utilized for trade purposes. The\ntaoiseach has pronounced Ideas about the\ncountry\u2019s sovereign rights and said rather\nrecently in an address concerning the\nnewly formed constitution: \u201cIn that\nconstitution the traditional aspirations of\nour people for national independence,\nnational unity and the unfettered con\ntrol of their domestic and foreign affairs\nhave been set as the basic principles of\nthe law by which we are henceforth to be\nKjverned.\u201d In that one statement you\nnd De Valera\u2019s hopes for an independ\nent Ireland.\nAs is the way of all men the prime\nminister has met with considerable\nopposition, but he continues his leader\nship in the way he thinks best for the\ncommon good and for a wholly inde\npendent Eire. He strongly opposes Brit\nish partition; a partition that makes one\nsmall portion of an already small coun\ntry not Irish but English. Why a border\nline in a country that from east to west\ncoast is a matter of not much more than\na hundred miles at some points and whose\nnorth and south coast are not more than a\nfew hundred miles apart, many ask? The\ntraveler traveling north out of Dublin\nwho has to show a passport after an hour\nor so train ride wonders what it\u2019s ail\nabout.\nWhatever the opposition De Valera has\na singleness of purpose. He wants noth\ning for himself; no Gaelic laudatory sal\nutations to coincide with German \u201cheils\u201d.\nHe is, it is safe to say, the world\u2019s most\nretiring and self-effacing leader. The\npeople of Ireland are not fleeing the coun\ntry from any rule that tells them what\npersonal liberties they cannot enjoy and\nwhat religious practices they are to fol\nlow. On the contrary it would seem that\nDe Valera is a leader with an under\nstandable purpose. He desires a united\nEire without partition and it looks as if\nhe had the admiration and good will of\ncountless people who regard him as a\nleader in the right direction.\nA Fine Example\nHitler hates everybody who opposes\nhim and many who don\u2019t oppose him,\nand the powers that are trying to stroke\nhis ruffled mane might consider the case\nof Laszlo Fodor, who committed the twin\natrocities of being born a Jew and of\ndrawing cartoons to the left of the\nextreme right advocated by the Great\nMan. Fodor was not mistreated phys\nically by the Nazis and was not sent to\na concentration camp. So perhaps a\ndispassionate examination of his story\nis all the more possible.\nFodor fought four years in the Austro\nHungarian army, coming up through\nthe ranks to a commission as a lieuten\nant. Germany was at that time glad\nto have the support of such men, even\nif they were of Jewish blood. After the\nwar, Fodor went to Berlin as a political\ncartoonist and editor. His success was\nquick and soon he had organized his own\nnewspaper syndicate. He prospered. Then\ncame the Nazi fury. Hitler\u2019s storm\ntroopers kicked Fodor out of his office,\ntold him to get out of the country. They\nallowed him to take his wife, his passport,\nand some clothes with him. The Nazis\ntook over Fodor\u2019s syndicate, which at\nthat time was making about $100,000 a\nyear.\nFodor went to Zurich, Switzerland,\nwhere, before Hitler, he had banked\n$10,000. With this he started a new syn\ndicate, but costs were high and he moved\nto Vienna. Fodor built another success\nful business in Vienna. Then the Nazis\nmoved in again. This time they confis\ncated everything. Fodor was in New\nYork when he got the news. Now 40\nyears old, he must start over again.\nSo that is just one of many. There is\nno sign that the Austrian Jews will receive\nbetter treatment than the German Jews.\nThe wave of suicides among the race indi\ncates how much mercy they expect from\nthe Great Man.\nVienna has been a city of great culture\nand accomplishment. There were many\nJews in high places in her famous medical\nschools and clinics. Jews were largely\nresponsible for the fame of Viennese\nopera, music, and theater. Those great\nJews will consider Laszlo Fodor compar\natively fortunate, for he was thousands\nof miles away when the booted terror\nmarched in.\nBut aside from the democracies\u2019 feel\nings about the fate of the Austrian Jews\nand the other groups which find dis\nfavor with Der Fuehrer, what are the\ndemocracies to expect when they attempt\nto deal with Hitler? They have the case\nof Laszlo Fodor as an example.\nSome White Elephant\nEvery so often New York state officials\napd legislators flirt with the general idea\nof purchasing the Bear Mountain Bridge\nfrom the corporation that now owns it.\nJust recently the General Assembly\npassed a bill to this effect, authorization\nfor purchase at an amount of $3,300,000\nbeing given by the lawmakers. But every\none doesn\u2019t feel that the state should buy\nthe big span across the Hudson River\njust above Peekskill. Governor Herbert\nH. Lehman has been urged to veto the\nmeasure.\nThe recommendation not to buy came\nfrom a Vassar College professor who said\nin part: \u201cIt can\u2019t escape you that the\nuniversal suspicion is that this bill is for\nthe purpose of taking a losing investment\noff the hands of owners of the bridge,\nthus enabling favorites of state officials\nto be reimbursed at the public\u2019s expense.\nWhy the secrecy? The public wants to\nknow who are the owners of the securi\nties of the bridge and it cannot find\nout.\nIf the Bear Mountain Bridge is going\nto be regarded as a white elephant, then\ncertainly so must a lot of these super\nhighways that states, counties and other\ngovernmental sub-divisions are building\ntoday. As a matter of strict fact wc\nalways were under the impression that\nthe Bear Mountain Bridge was really\nbuilt with a quasi-understanding that\nultimately the state would take over the\nownership of the structure. We may be\nwrong on that, as the bridge is owned and\noperated by a stock company now, but it\nwould seem that its ultimate ownership\nshould be vested in the people through\nthe state.\nWe doubt very much, too, if the bridge\nis such a white elephant as N. Y. state\ncritics of the bridge purchase bill claim\nit to be. As an engineering triumph it\ncertainly stands out; as an easy means\nof access between New York and Connec\nticut it supplies a great need.\nBetter public health service for Con-\nnecticut is advocated by Dr. Stanley H.\nOsborn, state commissioner of health. He\nurges cities and towns to cooperate with\ngroup leaders and physicians in health\nprotection. He recommends, and one\nsees the wisdom of it, that each local gov\nernment, devote itself to maintaining an\nadequate health service and bringing the\nsubject of health before the public re\npeatedly if not continuously. Here in\nour own city there is an efficient and\nsmooth functioning health department,\nwhich answers the requirements as out\nlined by the street commissioner who\nsays: \u201cthe time has come in Connecti\ncut when public health in the towns need\nnot lag behind that in our larger popula\ntion centers, but should advance just as\nit has in the more progressive cities.\u201d\nAnother old-time Connecticut news\npaper man has passed on. James F. Cos\ngrove, died the other day at the age of 77.\nHe had been associated with the Bridge\nport Post at the time he was stricken and\npreviously was associated with the Hart\nford Courant, the Bridgeport Telegram\nand the Danbury News. Mr. Cosgrove\ni was one of those seasoned newspapermen\nwho began as a copy boy, learning the\ncompositor\u2019s trade and through his var\nious experiences here and there as a prin\nter acquired a knowledge of the func\ntioning of many departments of a news\npaper. His experiences in newspaper\nwork brought him in contact with many\nwell known persons, including Mark\nTwain. He knew his business through\nsixty-three years service in same, which is\nquite a record.\nGiovanni Martinelli sang repeatedly at\nthe twenty-fifth anniversary of his asso\nciation with the Metropolitan Opera the\nother night. Martinelli has not missed\na season. He has been a consistent singer\nand has contributed greatly to the suc\ncess of the Metropolitan in his own style\nof singing, which is Martinelli.\nThe British have a neat phrase that\ntempers partisan hositility. They call the\nminority party in Parliament \u201cHis\nMajesty\u2019s loyal opposition.\u201d\nSelected Poem\nFLOWER TAPER\nHad my hands found, as white as silk.\nOnce in New England on a night\nOf stars and silenee did I come\nUpon a flower that was bright\nAs the millennium.\nNo other flower of its ilk\nIn all my lonely wanderings\n(Harold Vinal in the New York Tlmest\nAs if a million gusty springs\nHad by slow patience made it fair\nAnd brought its crystal cup to birth,\nAnd lit it like a taper there\nTo light the darkness of the earth.\nDaily Almanac\nMoon rises 1:25 a. m.\nSun rises 5:51 a. m.; sets 6:07 p. m.\nAll vehicles must be lighted thirty minutes\nafter sunset.\nSpring has officially arrived: many signs\nhave confirmed it in addition to the season\nal date. But we\u2019ve a few \u201cfreezes\" due in the\nnext month and a half. Peepers started their\nevening symphony choruses this week; we\nheard them Monday and Tuesday and Wed\nnesday. The old saying Is that peepers have\nto be frozen in three times before spring is\nactually here for good.\ni\nWe'd Like to Bat Out a Little Ultimatum, Too\nTH\u00a3 TREES ARE BURSTING\nINTO BLOOM ANt> THE BIRDS\nARE BEGINNING TO SING\nAMD THE FLOWERS ARE\nSTARTING TO COME OP AND\nWE\u2019RE GETTING INTO SOME\nNICE WEATHER NOW\nAND FOR THE NEXT FEW\nMONTHS YOU GUYS ARE\nGOING TO CRAWL UNDER\nSOMe ROCKS AND PIPE\nDOWN OR ELSE?\nTHC WORLD,\nSPRING, 1936\nCepyiicM. 19-8. r.t-A\n1\nRevenue On Punishment?\nTax Burden and Tax Purpose Are Two Different\nThings, as Recent Explanation of\nProf. Fairchild Shows.\nNEW HAVEN JOURNAL-COURIER\nProfessor Fairchild drew a per\nceptive distinction between tax bur\nden and tax purpose in his testi\nmony before the Senate finance\ncommittee. \u201cMy friends in industry\nare not crying so much about the\ntotal tax burden ,as about the meth\nod of imposing it and the conse\nquent uncertainties,\u201d he explained.\nHe\u2019s perfectly reconciled as we all\nmust be to a heavy tax burden in\nthe years to come. But there is a\nrather general suspicion among\nbusiness leaders that the tax burden\nisn\u2019t the only one they\u2019re asked to\nIn New York\nBV GEORGE ROSS\nNew York, March 24.\u2014Facts from\nthe File: Best place to see the most\npulchritudinous girls in town is a\nhamburger stand on 50th street aft\ner 2 a. m\u201e where showgrils assem\nble before going home.\nAlfred Lunt rehearses best under\nthe din of the Ninth avenue \"L.\u201d\nHardly ever recognized, too.\nRed suspenders are frowned upon\nin New York\u2019s fire department.\nIt is an optical feat to read a\nnewspaper by the lights of Times\nSquare, unquestionably the bright\nest corner in the world.\nAny pavement in the vicinity of\nthe Rialto which is thickly pop\nulated by unemployed actors and\nmusicians is designated as \u201cThe\nBeach.\u201d\nFully five per cent of Manhattan's\npopulation has never been over to\nBrooklyn, a few minutes away.\nMain Stem Sights\nStreet Sights: Alfred W. McCann,\nJr., the pure food commentator,\nlooks on interestedly as a health\nlecturer asks his audience if any\none knows anything about vitamins.\nFrances Farmer is startled as a\nnumber of shots ring out while she\u2019s\nstrolling down 42nd street\u2014but she\ncontinues her leisurely pace when\nshe ascertains it\u2019s from the shoot\ning gallery.\nGene Krupa, the famous drum\nmer, alights at Pennsylvania sta\ntion after a trip to the midwest in\nquest of swing musicians for his\nband and exclaims that he has\nhas some sensational finds.\nBroadway\u2019s Extremes\nPersonal Data: Broadway\u2019s young\nest showman Is Orson Welles, not\nyet 25.\nThe oldest of active producers is\nWilliam A. Brady, who has passed\nhis seventh decade\nVinton Freedley is the most en\nthusiastic fisherman along Theater\nRow; his weakness, baracuda.\nGeorge S. Kaufmann walks far\nther within the walls of one room,\nwhile writing a play, than any\nother dramatist.\nGeorge M. Cohan has the record\nfor more mileage than his contem\nporaries in open air strolls.\nLee Shubert\u2019s limousine was con\nstructed from special plans to pro\nvide an unusually wide rear com\npartment. And yet he prefers to\nride along side the chauffeur in the\nfront seat.\nNo one is so addicted to the long\ndistance phone call as is Jed Har\nris, California is a local call for\nhim.\n\nWhat Is In a Name\nName Oddities: Sammy Kaye\u2019s\nsecretary and arrangers sign their\nnames Sad Jollle and Pump\nHaendle, respectively.\nUday Shan-kar, the dancer, has\nthe most unusual name in the the\nater.\nAlexander Woollcott sees red if\ntypesetters spell his name incorrect\nly.\nBunny Berlgan got Ills nickname\nbecause his childhood playmates\nfound It easier to say than Bernard.\nThe glggllest chorus girl's name\nwithin this corner\u2019s memory is Gay\nOrlova. And another's; Ima Smile.\nshoulder. Besides it Is the burden\nof the enmity of the government the\ntaxes they yield, support.\nThere can be no doubt and no\nbody ever suggested there was, that\nthe surplus tax was aimed to re\nvise basic institutional practices of\nAmerican business. Some of the sur\ntaxes and estate taxes are certainly\ndesigned to pulverize wealth now\nheld narrowly. The tax on closely\nheld corporation, aimed frankly at\nliquidation of properties owned by\nfamily or small groups. The tax on\ncrpital gains, unbalanced as it was\nby allowances for capital losses, ts\nnot peculiar to the New Deal; yet\nenhancement in its use as a merely\npunitive and \u201ccorrective\u201d instru\nment is of the New Deal essence.\nThe trouble, that is, is that the\nadministration uses taxes as a lever\nto remake the system. Professor\nFairchild isn\u2019t of the school which\nattributes the whole decline to fed\neral finance policies, though New\nDeal responsibility on non-financia!\ngrounds 1s of course present. It's\nsimply that the spirit of buoyancy\nwhich nerves enterprise and so the\nundertaking of risk is shrivelled by\nthe sense the mightiest corporation\nin the society is against business as\ntraditionally run. It is one of the\ncomforts of the present state of af\nfairs that this understanding is\ngaining ground in congress.\nThus Senator Harrison\u2019s remarks\non the new tax bill and the non\nfiscal needs he hoped it would meet\nwas at refreshing and encouraging\nvariance from official New Deal\nideology. Not even Professor Ar\nnold's insistence that the whole\nbody of economic doctrine is mere\nfolklore has convinced the folks in\ncongress the faiths so represented\nshould not be maintained. One of\nProfessor Fairchild's points was that\nlow rates yielding something were\nbetter than trip-hammer exactions\nwhich never got past the enactment\nstage since no income bubbled up\nhigh enough to be affected. That\nis the beginning, though only the\nbeginning, of tax wisdom.\nA Book a Day\nA Book for Those\nWho Like Barrie\nOne opens an \u201cappreciation\" with\nmisgiving; but those who love J M.\nBarrie\u2019s fresh and tender humor\nand his gentle touch of mellow phil\nosophy will be happy to read Pro\nfessor James Roy\u2019s \u201cJ. M. Barrie;\nAn Appreciation,\" (Scribner's;\n$2.75).\nProfessor Roy lets Barrie do most\nof the talking. Being steeped as\nstrong as Scottish tea in Barrie\u2019s\nworks, he can quote any and all of\nthem for bits of biographical detail.\nAnd what could be finer?\nProfessor Roy bothers little with\ndetailing mere facts. If you are\nlooking for light on Barrie\u2019s mar\nriage and its strange failure, you\nwill be disappointed. He gingerly\ndismisses the Mary Ansell part of\nBarrie\u2019s life in a single, stark para\ngraph. He writes delightfully of the\nboyhood days in Kirriemuir\n(Thrums of the \u201cIdylls\u201d), giving\nplentiful evidence of Barrie's long\ndistance friendship with R. L S. in\nVailima, of the influence of Barrie\u2019s\nmother and of Carlyle.\nHe doesn\u2019t once use the word\n\"whimsical.\u201d Barrie had a shine to\nhi mas hard to catch as Peter Pan\u2019s\nshadow or the dazzle of moonlight\nin Lob\u2019s eerie garden. We are grate\nful to his appreciator for not at\ntempting this sort of interpretation.\nHe does recall an entrancing\npersonality and reminds us it would\ndo the world good to draw close to\nthe ribs of the fire for a moment\n\u201cin this prosent which is in such\na hurry to be the past\u201d and let\nthe Barrie light shine in\u2014the kind\nof light that lias gone out of art and\nlife.\n\u201cKingdoms pass but loving\nhearts and tenderness are of the\neternal essence of things.\" Or arc\nthey gone forever?\u2014 D. 8. E.\nQuestions and\nAnswers\nBy Frederick M. Kerby\nYOUR QUESTIONS ANSWERED\nEnclose a three-ccnt stamp tor\nreply when addressing any ques\ntion of fact or information to the\nWaterbury Democrat\u2019s Service Bu\nreau at Washington. Legal and\nmedical advice cannot be given,\nnor ran extended research be un\ndertaken. Be sure all mail is ad\ndressed to the WATERBURY\nDEMOCRAT\u2019S SERVICE BU\nREAU, 1013 Thirteenth Street,\nWashington, D. C.\nTHE EDITOR\nQ. For what word is Messrs, ail\nabbreviation?\nA. The French title, Messieurs.\nQ. Who publishes Moore\u2019s \u201cMete\norological Almanac and Weather\nGuide?\"\nA. Rand, McNally Co., Ill\nEighth avenue, New York city.\nQ. When did the Charleston, S.\nC., earthquake occur?\nA. Tuesday, August 31, 1886.\nQ. How many radios arc there in j\nhomes in the United States?\nTODAY\u2019S COMMON ERROR\nNever pronounce berceuse\u2014\nber-soos'; say, ber\u2019-surz.\nA. The January, 1938. issue of\n\u201cRadio Retailing,\u201d states that there\nare 26,428,797 homes with radios.\nQ. Is there a simple way to test\ncheese for ripeness?\nA. Place a small piece in your\nmouth. If it Is ripe enough, it, will\nmelt; green cheese will remain hard.\nQ. How many survivors of the\nUnion armies in the Civil war are\nliving?\nA. According to figures compiled\nby the Grand Army of the Republic,\nthere were about 3,325 survivors in\nthe fall of 1937. The death rate is\nabout 1,700 a year now.\nQ. In making out my federal in\ncome tax return may I deduct the\ncast of operating my automobile be\ntween my home and place of em\nployment?\nA. No.\nQ. Is a mixture of cream of tar\ntar and hydrogen peroxide likely to\nbe harmful if used as a clearifer for\nenamel?\nA. It will not harm the acid-re\nsistant type of vitreous enamel, but\nlong contact might damage non\nacid-resistant or ordinary type of\nvitreous enamel.\nQ. Is there a city or town named\nPawtucket in any state other than\nRhode Island?\nA. No.\nIf you want a copy of our book\nlet \u201cPopular Screen Stars\u201d write to\nWaterbury Democrat\u2019s Washington\nBureau, 1913 Thirteenth street,\nWashington, D. C. Enclose 10 cents\nin postage.\nTest Your\nKnowledge\nCan you answer seven of\nthese test questions? Turn to\nlast page for the answers.\n1. How many members of the U.\nS. Supreme Court did President\nTaft appoint during his term of of\nfice?\n2. In which state were the great\nest number of battles fought dur\ning the Civil War?\n3. What are the colors of Duke\nUniversity?\n4. What is the nickname for the\nstate of Idaho?\n5. Who was the first man to fly\nover both the North and South\nPoles?\n6. What is a spectroscope?\n7. How many feet are in one rod?\n8. For what do the Initials H.R.H.\nstand?\n9. What proportion of U. S. Sen\nators arc elected every two years?\n10. Name the largest national\ncemetery in the U. S.\nDaily\nWashington\nGO\nBy DBEW PEABSON\nMorgenthau Now Urges Relief Plan;\nBusiness Outlook and Events Abroad\nForce Him to Forget Balancing Budget;\nMcNutt Meets Secretly with Lewis\nWASHINGTON, March 24. Practically all the\nPresident\u2019s close advisers are strongly urging him to\nboost the new $1,000,000,000 regular relief budget, which\nhe recommended to Congress, to at least $1,500,000,000\nor still better $2,000,000,000.\nMiracle of miracles, even Sec\nretary Morgenthau is now veering\nto the spending point of view.\nUntil recently Morgenthau was\ndead against loosening the pub\nlic purse strings. Hopefully and\npersistently, he still clung to his\ngrand passion of balancing the\nbudget. But pessimistic business\nreports from private agents have\nconvinced him that this is a vain\nhope this year, that the country\nIs urgently in need of another\nshot in the arm from government\nspending.\nAlso playing an important\nrole in Yeung Henry's change\nof mind is the sinister European\nsituation. He is profoundly\nalarmed at what is happening\nthere, and fears that prolonga\ntion of the recession in this\ncountry would have grave econ\nomic repercussions abroad which\nmight be the final factor per\nripitating war.\nSo in the last few weeks Henry\nhas changed his tune. Though now\nleaning toward increasing expen\nditures. he doesn't go as far as\nmost of the other presidential ad\nvisers. who want Roosevelt to\nuntie the money bags and unleash\na big spending program.\nInner Struggle\nFederal Reserve Board Chair\nman Marriner S. Ecclcs, for ex\nample, has been trying for months\nto sell Roosevelt on a $3,000,\n000.000 spending plan.\nSiding with him are Bill Doug\nlas, chairman of the Securities\nand Exchange Commission, Relief\nAdministrator Harry Hopkins, Sec\nretary Ickes, Senator Bo!) LaFol\nlette and other militant inner\ncircle counselors.\nThey present two arguments:\nFIRST, that even if there is a\nslight business pickup this spring,\nas now scents likely, there is\nnothing in the cards to indicate\nthat the upturn will be more than\ntemporary. SECOND, every dol\nlar spent now by the govern\nment will be worth three dollars\nspent a year hence.\nIn other words, a S3.000,\n000,000 spending program now\nwill accomplish what it would\nrequire SIO.000,000,000 to do next\nyear if business is allowed to sag\nin the interim.\nIn private conversations, the\nPresident has expressed complete\nagreement with the Eccles-Doug\nlas-LaFollette viewpoint, though\nin practice he has followed Mor\ngen thau\u2019s previous don\u2019t-spend\nadvice.\nBut now with Morgenthau\nhimself beginning to concede the\nneed of more spending, the Eccles\ngroup is hopeful it can persuade\nRoosevelt to go still further and\njack up the new relief budget.\nIfoovcr Loves Wisconsin\nPresident James Bryant Conant\nof Harvard is the proud owner\nof a unique set of dishes. Each\npiece is stamped with the em\nblem of a prominent university.\nThe china was used at a din\nner which Conant once gave for\nHerbert Hoover. President Con\nant laughingly explained to Hoov\ner that the soup bowls bore the\nDartmouth insignia, the fish\nplates the emblem of Yale, and\nthe meat platters the seal of\nHarvard.\n\u201cI trust,\u201d added Mr. Hoover,\n\u201cthat the nuts arc served in\nWisconsin bowls\u201d.\nAustrian Minister\nFor Edgar Prochnik, the Aus\ntrian minister who had to fly\nthe Nazi swastika in front of his\nWashington Legation when Hit\nler inarched into Austria, the\nnumber 13 was most unlucky.\nFor Prochnik has been Austrian\nMinister to the United Staets for\nexactly 13 years\u2014and the 13th\nwill be his last.\nAlthough the oldest minister in\npoint of service, except for the\nSwiss, Prochnik now has the al\nternative of stooping to the much\nlower position of counselor of the\nGerman embassy, or going back\nto Austria to face a regime which\nhe opposes. Without money of\nhis own, Prochnik is in a tough\nspot.\nReturning to Austria, however,\nis the last thing he wants to\ndo. Ever since he graduated from\nthe Consular School in Vienna in\n1904, Prochnik has lived in the\nUnitedl States either as a consul\nor minister. Twice he has mar\nried American wives (Mary\nBatchelder of Chicago, who died\nin 1912, and Gretchen Stirling\nJames of Boston). He has four\nchildren living in the United\nStates.\nNOTE\u2014The ex-Austrian minis\nter is the only member of the\nDiplomatic Corps who can keep\na monocle in place while sing\ning.\nLewis and McNutt\nHigh Commissioner Paul Mc\nNutt passed up no bets during\nhis Washington sojourn in lay\ning the groundwork for his 1940\npresidential drive.\nIn addition to his widely pub\nlicized grandstand stunts, the.\nstatuesque Hoosier also was\nbusy behind the scenes, and\namong other things, had a secret\nmeeting with CIO boss, John L.\nLewis. The talk was aramged\nat McNutt\u2019s request by a mutual\nfriend and took place in the\nLewis\u2019 Alexandria home.\nThe evening\u2019s conversation it\nself was totally innocuous. At no\nlime was politics or any other\ncontroversial subject discussed\nThe talk centered chiefly about\nthe Far East and the interna\ntional situation.\nBut while on the surface noth\ning of importance transpired, the\nmeeting was not a waste of time\nfor either man. Behind the screen\nof casual chat they were able to\nget a close-up of each other and\nestablish a basis for possible fu\nture more important conversa\ntions. That McNutt definitely\nhas this in mind was guardedly\nindicated by his parting remark to\nLewis:\u2014\n\u201cI\u2019m returning in the latte?\npart of this year and I\u2019d like\nto talk to you again.\u201d\nNOTE\u2014Lewis was invited to tin\nbig reception staged for McNutt,\nbut he got wind that it was se\ncretly planned to photograph liir;\nas he greeted McNutt in the rr\nceiving line. So the big mir\nstayed at home.\nMerry-Go-Rouiul\nThe General Accounting Offi.\nmay claim to be the \u201cWatchdc\nof the Treasury\u201d but it ha\nnothing on Theodore B. Nickson\nController of the Federal Hous\ning Administration. He is the\nchampion penny-pincher of the\ngovernment. If the bi-monthly\nsalary of an FHA employe comes\nto a fraction of a cent, he doc\nnot get the penny, although that\nIs the general rule in the gov\nernment service Senator Burt\nWheeler has a clerk on his con\ngressional payroll who spends\nmuch time writing a column foi\nMontana newspapers. The ar\nticles, distributed free, boos:\nWheeler to the skies and smear\nSenator Jim Murray and Reprc\nsenlative Jerry O\u2019Connell, botl\nadministration supporters\n(Copyright. 1938, by United\nFeature Syndicate, Inc.)\nPress Comment\nWELL, WHAT'S THE MATTER\nWITH IT?\n(New Haven Journal-Courier)\nWe should like to rise up in our\nplace and rebuke the calumniators\nof New England weather. Will any\none of them have the fortitude to\nstep forth and state in precise and\nfactual terms what the matter was\nwith yesterday? We lay a little late\nfor us, and home thoughts of the\ncoal bin were the first to cross our\nemerging mind. We looked at the\nwindow, and the sun poked a scin\ntillating finger through: we noticed\nthat there was a birdcry in the\ndistance and we were up and out\nto investigate. And we found the\nyellow crocuses in full career be\nside the front porch.\nNow what makes us suddenly\nangry at those who deprecate New\nEngland weather is that all this\noccurred on the first, precisely the\nfirst, morning of spring. The keepers\nof the celestial weather-bins could\nnot have hit it on the nose more\nperfectly: the calendar had promis\ned us and the weather kept the\npledge. The thermometer on the\nback porch was 62 at eight a. m.,\nand was climbing when we left for\nwork. We put our battered over\ncoat aside with the reverence due\na veteran, now, of many meteoro\nlogical battles and stepped forth,\nfeeling a lot like Baldur, and a little\nlike Thor. (We trust it hasn\u2019t snow\ned by the times this gets into print.)\nOFF THE RECORD\nB> Ed Reed\nII. i'i\n1931. Th*\nMl Tnaum Ujradit***\n\"Be patient! It's almost live\u2014she\u2019ll be out any minute now.\"","height":"28120","width":"20560"}}
